👉 Think of it like downloading updates and installing them immediately.

💡 Summary:
Command	What it Does	Safe?	Notes
git fetch	Only downloads changes	✅ Safe	You merge manually later
git pull	Downloads + merges	⚠️ Can cause conflicts	Equivalent to git fetch + git merge

In simple terms:

Use git fetch when you want to see what’s new.

Use git pull when you’re ready to get and apply the new changes.

Q2 : implement redis cache in spring boot application? 
Redis is a kind of database
Implementing Redis cache in a Spring Boot application is a common way to improve performance and reduce database load.
Below is a complete step-by-step guide with explanations and code examples.

🧰 1. Add Dependencies

If you’re using Maven, add the following dependencies to your pom.xml:

<dependencies>
    <!-- Spring Boot Starter for Redis -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-redis</artifactId>
    </dependency>

    <!-- Spring Boot Cache abstraction -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-cache</artifactId>
    </dependency>

    <!-- (Optional) Jackson for Redis serialization -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.fasterxml.jackson.core</groupId>
        <artifactId>jackson-databind</artifactId>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>

⚙️ 2. Configure Redis in application.properties or application.yml
Using application.properties
spring.data.redis.host=localhost
spring.data.redis.port=6379
spring.data.redis.password=
spring.cache.type=redis


If you’re using Docker, you can run Redis locally with:

docker run -d -p 6379:6379 redis

🧩 3. Enable Caching in Your Application

Add the @EnableCaching annotation to your main Spring Boot application class.

import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.cache.annotation.EnableCaching;

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableCaching
public class RedisCacheApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(RedisCacheApplication.class, args);
    }
}

Sure 🙂 — here’s a simple explanation:

### 🧩 What `@EnableCaching` does:

`@EnableCaching` **turns on Spring’s caching feature** in your application.

### 💡 In short:

When you add `@EnableCaching`, Spring will start **looking for methods with caching annotations** (like `@Cacheable`, `@CachePut`, `@CacheEvict`) and automatically handle storing and retrieving data from the cache for you.

### 🚀 Benefit:

It makes your app **faster** and **more efficient** because:

* Spring will **skip expensive operations** (like database calls) if the result is already cached.
* You don’t have to manually write code to manage the cache — Spring does it for you.

### 🧠 Example:

Without `@EnableCaching`:
Every time you call `getUserById("123")`, it hits the database.

With `@EnableCaching`:
Spring first checks Redis (the cache).
If user `"123"` is already there → returns it immediately (no DB call).
If not → fetches from DB, saves it in Redis, and returns it.

👉 **In one line:**
`@EnableCaching` activates Spring’s automatic caching system to speed up your app and reduce unnecessary work.


🧠 4. Configure Redis Template (optional but recommended)

If you want to control serialization or handle custom objects, create a configuration class:

import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.data.redis.connection.RedisConnectionFactory;
import org.springframework.data.redis.core.RedisTemplate;
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer;
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.StringRedisSerializer;

@Configuration
public class RedisConfig {

    @Bean
    public RedisTemplate<String, Object> redisTemplate(RedisConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {
        RedisTemplate<String, Object> template = new RedisTemplate<>();
        template.setConnectionFactory(connectionFactory);

        template.setKeySerializer(new StringRedisSerializer());
        template.setValueSerializer(new GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer());
        template.setHashKeySerializer(new StringRedisSerializer());
        template.setHashValueSerializer(new GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer());

        template.afterPropertiesSet();
        return template;
    }
}

Of course 😊 here’s the **super simple** version:

### 💡 What this class does:

This class tells Spring **how to talk to Redis**.

### ⚙️ In plain words:

* It **creates a RedisTemplate** — a tool your app uses to read and write data in Redis.
* It says:

  * “🔑 Store keys as **text** (easy to read).”
  * “📦 Store values as **JSON** (so we can save whole Java objects, not just strings).”

### 🧠 Simple meaning:

> This class helps your app **save and read data from Redis in a nice, readable way**, using strings for keys and JSON for data.


if u still dont use this class because its optional : 

Yes 👍 — it will **still work** even if you don’t use this class.

### 💡 Here’s why:

Spring Boot already provides a **default `RedisTemplate`** and **default serializers**, so caching and basic Redis operations will work out of the box.

### 🧩 But… without this class:

* Keys and values might be stored in **binary format** (not readable in Redis CLI).
* Custom Java objects might not be stored or retrieved properly (you could get weird unreadable data or errors).

### ✅ So:

* **For simple data** (like strings, numbers): works fine without this class.
* **For complex objects** (like `User`, `Product`, etc.): better to add this config — it makes everything easier and safer.

👉 **In short:**
It will still work, but adding this class makes Redis data **clearer, more readable, and more reliable** — especially when caching custom objects.


In my project, I used Spring Cache with @Cacheable, so I did not need RedisTemplate. Spring Boot handled storing and retrieving data from Redis automatically. RedisTemplate is used when we need more control over Redis operations.

🚀 5. Use Caching in Your Service Layer

You can now use caching annotations:

@Cacheable — caches the result

@CachePut — updates the cache

@CacheEvict — removes from the cache

Example:

import org.springframework.cache.annotation.Cacheable;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class UserService {

    // Example: Fetch user by ID (simulating DB call)
    @Cacheable(value = "users", key = "#id") // 'value' defines the cache name, 'key' defines how the cache entry is identified 
    public String getUserById(String id) {
        System.out.println("Fetching user from database for ID: " + id);
        return "User_" + id;
    }
}


When you call getUserById("101"):

The first call hits the database (or your logic).

The result is cached in Redis under key users::101.

Subsequent calls return instantly from cache.

🧹 6. Cache Eviction Example

If data changes and you want to clear or update the cache:

import org.springframework.cache.annotation.CacheEvict;
import org.springframework.cache.annotation.CachePut;

@Service
public class UserService {

    @CachePut(value = "users", key = "#id")
    public String updateUser(String id, String name) {
        System.out.println("Updating user in DB and cache for ID: " + id);
        return name;
    }

    @CacheEvict(value = "users", key = "#id")
    public void deleteUser(String id) {
        System.out.println("Deleting user and removing from cache for ID: " + id);
    }
}

🧩 7. Verify in Redis CLI

Run the Redis CLI to see stored keys:

redis-cli
127.0.0.1:6379> keys *


You should see something like:

1) "users::101"

keys * → shows all the keys saved in Redis (like a list of what’s stored).

get <key> → shows the actual data for that key.

✅ Summary
Step	Description
1	Add Redis and cache dependencies
2	Configure Redis connection
3	Enable caching (@EnableCaching)
4	Optionally configure RedisTemplate
5	Use @Cacheable, @CachePut, @CacheEvict
6	Test and verify keys in Redis 

