  or 

  Advanced Concurrency (Synchronization) in Java is used to safely handle multiple threads working at the same time on shared data or resources. It helps prevent problems like incorrect data updates and thread conflicts. It is an improved and more flexible version of the normal `synchronized` keyword and provides features like better control over locking, allowing multiple readers, and limiting how many threads can access a resource simultaneously.


* Main types:

  1. **ReentrantLock**
  2. **ReadWriteLock**
  3. **Semaphore**


     there are total 3 types of Advanced Concurrency (Synchronization)
	 1 : ReentrantLock
     2 : ReentrantReadWriteLock / ReadWriteLock
     3 : Semaphore

    1 : ReentrantLock : This code is about using a ReentrantLock with tryLock() in Java to handle thread locking safely.

      class TryLockExample {
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public void attemptTask() {
        try {
            if (lock.tryLock(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) {   // 🕐 Try to get the lock for 2 seconds
                try {
                    System.out.println("Lock acquired, performing task...");
                    Thread.sleep(1000); // simulate work
                } finally {
                    lock.unlock(); // 🔓 Always unlock after work
                }
            } else {
                System.out.println("Couldn't acquire lock within 2 seconds, exiting...");
            }
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

The 2 seconds in tryLock(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS)

That 2 seconds is only the maximum waiting time to get the lock,
not the time limit for doing the work.

✅ So what happens:

Suppose Thread B is waiting for the lock for up to 2 seconds.

If within that time Thread A releases the lock,
→ then Thread B immediately acquires it.

Once B has the lock, it can do its work peacefully —
even if it takes longer than 2 seconds to finish.

Timeout in ReentrantLock is ONLY for waiting to acquire the lock — not for how long you can work after taking the lock.

💬 Example:

B calls tryLock(2, TimeUnit.SECONDS)

A releases after 1 second → B gets the lock.

B now does its work (maybe for 5 seconds). That’s totally fine ✅

In short:
2 seconds = “I’ll wait for up to 2 seconds to get the lock.”
Once you get the lock → you can work for as long as you need.
	
	 
2 : ReentrantReadWriteLock / ReadWriteLock	: Many can read, only one can write

class SharedData {
    private int data = 0;
    private final ReentrantReadWriteLock rwLock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();

    public void write(int value) {
        rwLock.writeLock().lock();   // 🔒 Only one thread can write
        try {
            data = value;
            System.out.println("Written: " + value);
        } finally {
            rwLock.writeLock().unlock(); // 🔓 Unlock after writing
        }
    }

    public void read() {
        rwLock.readLock().lock();   // 🔒 Many threads can read at once
        try {
            System.out.println("Read: " + data);
        } finally {
            rwLock.readLock().unlock(); // 🔓 Unlock after reading
        }
    }
}


Simple Explanation:

The class has a shared variable data.

We use ReentrantReadWriteLock to manage access to it.

🟢 Read Lock → Many threads can read at the same time (no problem).
🔴 Write Lock → Only one thread can write at a time (others wait).

💬 Example in real life:

Think of it like a library:

Many people can read books (read lock).

But when someone wants to update books (write lock), everyone else must wait.

👉 In short:
This code makes sure that reading can happen together, but writing happens one at a time safely. 
	 
	 
3 : Semaphore
class ParkingLot {
    private final Semaphore slots = new Semaphore(3); // only 3 cars allowed

    public void parkCar(String carName) {
        try {
            slots.acquire(); // 🚗 take a slot (enter)
            System.out.println(carName + " parked.");
            Thread.sleep(1000); // stay parked for a while
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        } finally {
            System.out.println(carName + " left.");
            slots.release(); // 🚗 leave the slot
        }
    }
}

Simple Explanation:

The Semaphore controls how many threads (cars) can access something at the same time.

Here, only 3 cars can park at once.

If a 4th car comes, it must wait until one of the cars leaves.

💬 Real-life Example:

Imagine a parking lot with 3 parking spaces.
When a space is free → a car enters.
When all are full → other cars must wait until someone leaves.

👉 In short:
This code controls how many threads can enter a section of code at once — perfect for limited resources.


Q7 : synchronized vs volatile vs atomic in java ? 
Ans  : all these three things are used to achieve thread safety in java 
     
  	 1 : synchronized : 
	     Used with methods or code blocks.
		 Allows only one thread at a time to run that code.
		 Gives both atomicity (one-at-a-time) and visibility (latest value shared).
		 👉Like putting a lock on a room — one thread enters, others wait.
	 
	 2 : volatile : 
	     Used with variables — it makes sure other threads see the updated value of the variable, instead of reading it 
		 from their local thread cache.
		 Makes sure all threads see the latest value of a variable.
		 Doesn’t stop threads from changing it at the same time.
		 👉 Just keeps the value fresh.
		 
     3 : atomic	 
	    

		---

		### 💡 **Atomic means:**

		Only **one thread** can change the value **at a time**,
		so the value always stays **correct**.

		---

		### 🧠 Example:

		Many people adding 1 to the same number —
		**atomic** makes sure they don’t all add at the same time and cause mistakes.

		---

		👉 **In one line:**
		**Atomic = safe number that changes correctly when many threads use it.**
		
		import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;

public class AtomicExample {
    // shared variable
    static AtomicInteger count = new AtomicInteger(0);

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // create two threads
        Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
                count.incrementAndGet(); // safely add 1
            }
        });

        Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
                count.incrementAndGet(); // safely add 1
            }
        });

        t1.start();
        t2.start();

        try {
            t1.join();
            t2.join();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        System.out.println("Final Count: " + count);
    }
}


Two threads (t1 and t2) both add 1 to the same number 1000 times.

Because we use AtomicInteger, both threads can add safely.

Final result will always be 2000 ✅

If we used a normal int instead of AtomicInteger,
the result might be less than 2000 because threads would clash.

AtomicInteger as a kind of wrapper class around an int value —
but with extra powers for thread safety

AtomicLong - Works like AtomicInteger, but for long values.

AtomicBoolean - For boolean (true/false) values
	 
	 
