### 🧭 **1️⃣ Orchestration-based Saga**

* There is **one central boss (Orchestrator)**.
* It tells each service what to do — one by one.
* If something fails, the boss tells others to **undo** their work.

🧠 *Think of it like:*
A **trip planner** who says:
“Book flight → then hotel → then taxi”
If taxi fails → “cancel hotel → cancel flight”

---

### 🔔 **2️⃣ Choreography-based Saga**

* There is **no boss**.
* Each service **listens to events** and reacts.
* If one fails, it sends an event so others know to **cancel themselves**.

🧠 *Think of it like:*
All services **talk to each other automatically** —
when flight is booked, hotel books itself, then taxi books, etc.
If taxi fails → it sends a message → flight and hotel cancel.

---

### 🧩 **Simple difference**

| Type             | Who controls the flow? | Example                                       |
| ---------------- | ---------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| 🧭 Orchestration | One central service    | “Trip Manager” controls booking steps         |
| 🔔 Choreography  | Services themselves    | Services react to events (no central control) |

---

### ✅ **In one line:**

> **Orchestration** → One boss gives orders 👨‍💼
> **Choreography** → Everyone follows the music 🎶 (events)/everyone knows their role and reacts to events

